1
00:00:05,441 --> 00:00:07,001
(INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS)

2
00:00:18,921 --> 00:00:21,401
Don't let us down now, Valkyrie.

3
00:00:22,921 --> 00:00:24,081
Fingers crossed, Alan.

4
00:00:24,161 --> 00:00:26,481
(CHUCKLES)
Yeah, I got everything crossed.

5
00:00:26,561 --> 00:00:27,601
Okay, people.

6
00:00:29,321 --> 00:00:30,681
Transmission arriving in...

7
00:00:30,761 --> 00:00:32,401
MAN: (OVER PA)
And we are standing by. Countdown...

8
00:00:32,681 --> 00:00:33,801
-Ten...
-(COUNTER BEEPS)

9
00:00:34,001 --> 00:00:35,121
-Nine.
-(COUNTER BEEPS)

10
00:00:35,281 --> 00:00:36,401
-Eight.
-(COUNTER BEEPS)

11
00:00:36,481 --> 00:00:38,441
-Seven, six.
-(COUNTER BEEPING)

12
00:00:38,601 --> 00:00:40,641
-Five, four.
-(COUNTER BEEPING)

13
00:00:40,881 --> 00:00:41,921
-Three.
-(COUNTER BEEPS)

14
00:00:42,081 --> 00:00:43,081
-Two.
-(COUNTER BEEPS)

15
00:00:43,161 --> 00:00:44,241
-One.
-(COUNTER BEEPS)

16
00:00:44,321 --> 00:00:45,361
(POWER DRAINS)

17
00:00:45,441 --> 00:00:46,721
Sorry, I could never resist a countdown.

18
00:00:46,961 --> 00:00:49,081
-Who the hell are you?
-BILL: Is this Neil Armstrong?

19
00:00:49,601 --> 00:00:50,641
What?

20
00:00:50,881 --> 00:00:51,961
Neil Armstrong.

21
00:00:52,601 --> 00:00:53,681
First man on the moon.

22
00:00:53,761 --> 00:00:55,041
Not quite the first.

23
00:00:55,401 --> 00:00:57,161
What, you mean he wasn't
the first man on the moon?

24
00:00:57,241 --> 00:00:59,001
That is such a human-centric question.

25
00:00:59,401 --> 00:01:00,801
I'm the human in this setup.

26
00:01:01,241 --> 00:01:02,241
NARDOLE: She is, actually.

27
00:01:02,641 --> 00:01:03,881
A bit embarrassing, really.

28
00:01:04,721 --> 00:01:06,681
Who are you people?

29
00:01:06,921 --> 00:01:08,721
DOCTOR: Friendly aliens. Don't mind us.

30
00:01:08,881 --> 00:01:10,041
Just a day out for the kids.

31
00:01:13,281 --> 00:01:14,561
-It's from the chief.
-Is it?

32
00:01:14,641 --> 00:01:17,721
Oh, yes, that's right. Authorising us
to go anywhere we please. So.

33
00:01:18,841 --> 00:01:20,041
Valkyrie.

34
00:01:20,361 --> 00:01:22,121
Valkyrie is...

35
00:01:24,041 --> 00:01:27,841
Probing the Martian ice caps
with a new kind of camera on board.

36
00:01:28,001 --> 00:01:31,521
Uses a different spectrum to see

37
00:01:31,601 --> 00:01:33,241
under the poles

38
00:01:33,321 --> 00:01:34,961
and beam back pictures.

39
00:01:35,921 --> 00:01:37,161
(TYPING ON KEYBOARD)

40
00:01:41,601 --> 00:01:43,041
What the hell...

41
00:01:52,881 --> 00:01:54,881
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

42
00:02:40,641 --> 00:02:42,281
DOCTOR: Mars, 1881.

43
00:02:42,481 --> 00:02:44,721
Or thereabouts. According to the TARDIS,

44
00:02:44,801 --> 00:02:47,641
that's when the message was made.
Though we may be a bit early.

45
00:02:47,961 --> 00:02:50,241
So, there were humans on Mars
in Victorian times.

46
00:02:50,521 --> 00:02:51,641
No.

47
00:02:52,481 --> 00:02:53,481
There weren't.

48
00:02:54,641 --> 00:02:55,761
NARDOLE: The TARDIS registered

49
00:02:55,841 --> 00:02:58,401
multiple life forms
below the surface, sir.

50
00:02:59,041 --> 00:03:00,801
It seems like the best place to look.

51
00:03:01,521 --> 00:03:03,841
BILL: Maybe someone's been
messing around with time.

52
00:03:03,921 --> 00:03:05,961
-Like in The Terminator.
-The Terminator?

53
00:03:06,041 --> 00:03:07,081
It's a movie.

54
00:03:07,481 --> 00:03:09,601
-BILL: You haven't seen it?
-I'm a very busy man.

55
00:03:10,001 --> 00:03:11,001
BILL: Well, you'd like it.

56
00:03:11,241 --> 00:03:12,361
It's got killer robots.

57
00:03:12,881 --> 00:03:14,241
Oh, I'll put it on the list.

58
00:03:15,441 --> 00:03:17,161
Even if there are people here,

59
00:03:17,241 --> 00:03:19,801
why would they bother writing messages
on the surface of the planet?

60
00:03:20,041 --> 00:03:21,721
State visit, patriotic fervour.

61
00:03:23,001 --> 00:03:24,641
Rogue graffiti artist.

62
00:03:27,081 --> 00:03:28,121
Doctor...

63
00:03:31,161 --> 00:03:32,161
I see it

64
00:03:45,801 --> 00:03:48,361
Oh, if there's fire,
there's got to be oxygen.

65
00:03:48,481 --> 00:03:49,761
Wait wait. Let's not be rash.

66
00:03:50,001 --> 00:03:51,761
-Okay.
-I'll go first.

67
00:03:53,801 --> 00:03:54,801
What are you doing?

68
00:03:55,241 --> 00:03:57,561
Fire, oxygen. Basic physics, innit?

69
00:03:59,081 --> 00:04:00,361
Could have been basic death.

70
00:04:01,321 --> 00:04:02,521
(HELMETS HISSING)

71
00:04:03,401 --> 00:04:05,281
Wait, how can there be oxygen here?

72
00:04:07,201 --> 00:04:09,761
The indigenous Martians
were superb engineers.

73
00:04:11,681 --> 00:04:13,961
Mind you, there's a lot here
that doesn't make sense.

74
00:04:14,721 --> 00:04:17,001
Oh, it's like the underground tunnels
in 7he Thing.

75
00:04:18,121 --> 00:04:19,121
The what?

76
00:04:19,401 --> 00:04:22,681
BILL: It's a movie.
You'd like that one too. Everybody dies.

77
00:04:24,921 --> 00:04:25,921
Whoa!

78
00:04:26,001 --> 00:04:27,081
(BILL SCREAMING)

79
00:04:29,561 --> 00:04:30,561
(GRUNTS)

80
00:04:30,801 --> 00:04:31,801
(GROANS)

81
00:04:32,161 --> 00:04:33,161
Bill!

82
00:04:33,761 --> 00:04:34,761
Bill!

83
00:04:35,121 --> 00:04:36,121
Bill!

84
00:04:36,641 --> 00:04:38,481
Bill! Hang on.

85
00:04:38,921 --> 00:04:39,921
DOCTOR: We'll find a way down.

86
00:04:40,801 --> 00:04:41,921
Go back to the TARDIS.

87
00:04:42,161 --> 00:04:44,001
Get ropes, lifting gear,
anything you can find.

88
00:04:44,361 --> 00:04:45,441
(WHIMPERS)

89
00:04:56,241 --> 00:04:57,241
(BEEPS)

90
00:04:58,361 --> 00:04:59,401
Oh!

91
00:05:00,081 --> 00:05:01,601
-(WHIMPERS)
-(ALARM RINGING)

92
00:05:13,361 --> 00:05:15,641
Nardole, what the hell are you doing?

93
00:05:16,601 --> 00:05:17,601
(COUGHS)

94
00:05:23,961 --> 00:05:25,081
(BEEPS)

95
00:05:25,281 --> 00:05:26,281
(WHIRRING)

96
00:05:30,681 --> 00:05:32,281
(HEAVY STOMPING)

97
00:05:53,481 --> 00:05:54,481
(BEEPING STOPS)

98
00:05:55,721 --> 00:05:56,961
(DOOR OPENING)

99
00:05:59,681 --> 00:06:00,681
(LOW GROWLING)

100
00:06:02,881 --> 00:06:04,441
So, this could go very well.

101
00:06:05,321 --> 00:06:06,561
Or very badly.

102
00:06:07,641 --> 00:06:08,641
(HISSING)

103
00:06:29,481 --> 00:06:30,641
Halt!

104
00:06:33,001 --> 00:06:34,001
I say,

105
00:06:34,841 --> 00:06:36,281
we weren't expecting company.

106
00:06:39,201 --> 00:06:40,201
Right.

107
00:06:40,681 --> 00:06:42,001
(WHIRRING)

108
00:06:44,921 --> 00:06:45,921
Uh...

109
00:06:46,401 --> 00:06:47,401
Yeah...

110
00:06:50,041 --> 00:06:51,041
Right.

111
00:06:53,721 --> 00:06:54,721
No...

112
00:07:00,001 --> 00:07:01,481
By the moons, I honour thee.

113
00:07:03,321 --> 00:07:04,401
I'm the Doctor.

114
00:07:05,081 --> 00:07:06,081
What is your name?

115
00:07:06,321 --> 00:07:07,681
(HISSES)

116
00:07:08,921 --> 00:07:11,481
I know your people of old. I was once

117
00:07:11,561 --> 00:07:13,881
honorary guardian of the Tythonian Hive.

118
00:07:15,521 --> 00:07:16,641
-(GUN COCKS)
-MAN: Don't move.

119
00:07:17,201 --> 00:07:18,521
I'll sort this bugger out.

120
00:07:18,641 --> 00:07:20,801
No, no, no, no, no.
You don't understand.

121
00:07:20,881 --> 00:07:22,241
This creature is no threat.

122
00:07:22,321 --> 00:07:23,761
He may look like a monster to you...

123
00:07:23,841 --> 00:07:24,921
(GUNSHOT)

124
00:07:25,361 --> 00:07:26,601
I wasn't talking to you.

125
00:07:29,481 --> 00:07:30,481
You all right, Friday?

126
00:07:31,521 --> 00:07:32,521
FRIDAY: Sir.

127
00:07:33,121 --> 00:07:34,601
Who are you and what the devil
are you doing here?

128
00:07:34,841 --> 00:07:36,441
Well, I could ask you the same question.

129
00:07:36,681 --> 00:07:37,681
And I will.

130
00:07:58,481 --> 00:07:59,761
(BEEPING)

131
00:08:02,121 --> 00:08:03,121
Hello?

132
00:08:03,881 --> 00:08:05,121
Hello, miss?

133
00:08:05,681 --> 00:08:07,401
I was wondering
if I could ask for your help.

134
00:08:07,481 --> 00:08:09,681
Uh, I need to get to Mars...

135
00:08:09,761 --> 00:08:12,481
Er, well, I need to
get back to Mars in fact.

136
00:08:12,561 --> 00:08:15,081
Erm, and it's a little bit urgent,

137
00:08:15,161 --> 00:08:16,801
only the TARDIS is acting up.

138
00:08:16,881 --> 00:08:19,681
And I was wondering if you could tell me
how to fix...

139
00:08:19,761 --> 00:08:20,761
MISSY: (OVER SPEAKER) Of course, I can.

140
00:08:21,761 --> 00:08:22,761
Oh.

141
00:08:23,081 --> 00:08:25,161
Right. Well, thank you.

142
00:08:25,521 --> 00:08:27,561
MISSY: It's probably easier
if I just show you.

143
00:08:28,441 --> 00:08:30,041
Oh. Erm...

144
00:08:31,561 --> 00:08:32,561
Er...

145
00:08:33,561 --> 00:08:35,001
COLONEL: Indian or China, my dear?

146
00:08:36,441 --> 00:08:37,441
BILL: Erm...

147
00:08:38,761 --> 00:08:40,521
(STAMMERS) I don't know...

148
00:08:41,201 --> 00:08:42,201
China?

149
00:08:42,321 --> 00:08:43,481
(POURING TEA)

150
00:08:45,601 --> 00:08:46,841
(WHISPERING) Where's Nardole?

151
00:08:47,681 --> 00:08:48,681
Um...

152
00:08:51,321 --> 00:08:53,041
Well, he seems to have taken the TARDIS.

153
00:08:53,121 --> 00:08:54,361
-What?
-It's...

154
00:08:55,041 --> 00:08:57,521
I'm sure it's only
a temporary thing, you know,

155
00:08:57,601 --> 00:08:59,241
but it means that
for the time being we're...

156
00:09:00,161 --> 00:09:02,681
(CLEARS THROAT) Stuck here on Mars.

157
00:09:02,761 --> 00:09:03,761
You were saying, Colonel.

158
00:09:04,041 --> 00:09:05,441
Oh, uh, well, yes.

159
00:09:05,521 --> 00:09:08,761
(CLEARS THROAT) I was stationed
out there, er, South Africa.

160
00:09:08,841 --> 00:09:11,441
One day, I came across something
in the veld.

161
00:09:11,801 --> 00:09:14,161
Something that was clearly
not of this Earth.

162
00:09:14,801 --> 00:09:16,521
An inter-planetary vessel.

163
00:09:17,401 --> 00:09:20,881
I found Friday here, on board,
in a sort of coma.

164
00:09:21,241 --> 00:09:22,241
Half dead.

165
00:09:22,961 --> 00:09:23,961
Why do you call him that?

166
00:09:24,881 --> 00:09:25,881
Man Friday?

167
00:09:26,721 --> 00:09:28,201
As in Robinson Crusoe?

168
00:09:30,201 --> 00:09:31,201
So...

169
00:09:32,521 --> 00:09:33,521
According to this,

170
00:09:33,841 --> 00:09:35,521
you've been on board Friday's ship

171
00:09:36,001 --> 00:09:37,121
the whole time?

172
00:09:37,441 --> 00:09:38,921
Yes, but we were...

173
00:09:39,801 --> 00:09:41,201
That was... That sounds...

174
00:09:41,481 --> 00:09:43,081
-That sounds... Quite...
-Convincing.

175
00:09:43,201 --> 00:09:44,801
That sounds... Yes, that's right.

176
00:09:45,801 --> 00:09:46,841
On his ship.

177
00:09:50,001 --> 00:09:52,281
Well, I suppose it was
pretty roomy, what! (LAUGHS)

178
00:09:52,641 --> 00:09:54,081
(NERVOUS LAUGHTER)

179
00:09:55,081 --> 00:09:57,561
-It was, yes. Wasn't it? Very roomy.
-Yes.

180
00:09:58,841 --> 00:10:01,321
But the whole, you know, I mean,
getting on board...

181
00:10:01,801 --> 00:10:03,001
I mean, that's all... (EXHALES)

182
00:10:04,001 --> 00:10:05,201
It's all a bit hazy.

183
00:10:05,801 --> 00:10:08,401
Maybe you could tell us everything.

184
00:10:08,841 --> 00:10:10,321
Yes, well, erm... (CLEARS THROAT)

185
00:10:11,041 --> 00:10:12,241
After I woke him up,

186
00:10:13,041 --> 00:10:14,481
Friday asked for my help.

187
00:10:14,561 --> 00:10:16,001
To repair his spaceship?

188
00:10:16,121 --> 00:10:17,601
Yes, and to bring him home.

189
00:10:17,721 --> 00:10:19,881
In return for what?

190
00:10:20,121 --> 00:10:21,161
Er...

191
00:10:21,601 --> 00:10:22,601
Well, now...

192
00:10:23,681 --> 00:10:24,761
That is the question.

193
00:10:24,881 --> 00:10:25,881
(EXPLOSION)

194
00:10:27,041 --> 00:10:28,601
Prepare to fire!

195
00:10:30,241 --> 00:10:33,081
On the double! Go, go, go!

196
00:10:33,401 --> 00:10:35,881
CATCHLOVE: Friday helped
us build the Gargantua.

197
00:10:36,521 --> 00:10:38,201
A remarkable piece of mining equipment

198
00:10:38,321 --> 00:10:40,161
fashioned from
one of his ship's artillery.

199
00:10:40,521 --> 00:10:41,521
(GROANS)

200
00:10:45,641 --> 00:10:46,681
(SOLDIER COUGHING)

201
00:10:48,241 --> 00:10:50,361
CATCHLOVE: He promised us
gemstones, you see.

202
00:10:50,721 --> 00:10:55,041
Silver, gold, treasure
beyond our wildest dreams.

203
00:10:55,401 --> 00:10:56,921
That's why you helped him come home.

204
00:11:00,041 --> 00:11:02,361
To claim Mars
in the name of Queen Victoria.

205
00:11:02,721 --> 00:11:04,161
To loot it of its riches.

206
00:11:04,481 --> 00:11:05,481
Stake a claim.

207
00:11:05,921 --> 00:11:07,601
The Red Planet turned pink.

208
00:11:08,201 --> 00:11:09,721
That was the general idea, old love.

209
00:11:11,161 --> 00:11:12,361
But there's nothing here.

210
00:11:13,201 --> 00:11:15,001
The whole show has been a ruddy washout.

211
00:11:15,481 --> 00:11:17,001
The ship crashed on landing.

212
00:11:17,321 --> 00:11:19,681
I go topside now and then to see
if I can repair the beggar.

213
00:11:21,161 --> 00:11:23,201
That's what I was doing
when I ran across you.

214
00:11:24,921 --> 00:11:25,921
And?

215
00:11:26,681 --> 00:11:29,201
-No joy so far.
-It could have been a fresh start.

216
00:11:29,921 --> 00:11:30,921
For all of us.

217
00:11:31,321 --> 00:11:32,481
But now...

218
00:11:33,081 --> 00:11:35,361
Supplies are running as low as morale.

219
00:11:36,401 --> 00:11:38,361
Things are pretty desperate, I'm afraid.

220
00:11:42,161 --> 00:11:43,561
(STOMPING)

221
00:11:54,161 --> 00:11:55,721
BILL: You told us why you came here.

222
00:11:56,681 --> 00:11:57,841
What does he get out of it?

223
00:11:59,241 --> 00:12:00,361
COLONEL: Nothing.

224
00:12:01,161 --> 00:12:02,161
BILL: Nothing?

225
00:12:02,361 --> 00:12:03,601
Well, he was hoping to find his people,

226
00:12:03,681 --> 00:12:05,761
but it appears that
he was asleep on that ship

227
00:12:05,841 --> 00:12:07,761
for much longer than he anticipated.

228
00:12:08,561 --> 00:12:09,761
Mars is dead.

229
00:12:10,321 --> 00:12:11,481
Dead as a coffin nail.

230
00:12:12,481 --> 00:12:13,961
Friday's the last of his kind.

231
00:12:15,641 --> 00:12:16,721
Is he now?

232
00:12:19,081 --> 00:12:21,041
BILL: You know what Friday is then?

233
00:12:21,121 --> 00:12:22,801
DOCTOR: He's an Ice Warrior.

234
00:12:23,201 --> 00:12:25,001
And they're the proper Martians, right?

235
00:12:25,081 --> 00:12:26,081
They belong here.

236
00:12:26,721 --> 00:12:29,441
Yes. The indigenous species.

237
00:12:29,921 --> 00:12:32,321
DOCTOR: An ancient reptilian race,
they build themselves as sort of

238
00:12:32,561 --> 00:12:35,281
bio-mechanical arm our for protection.
The creature within

239
00:12:36,121 --> 00:12:37,761
is at one with his carapace.

240
00:12:39,161 --> 00:12:40,241
DOCTOR: The Ice Warriors.

241
00:12:41,041 --> 00:12:43,081
They could build a city under the sand,

242
00:12:43,721 --> 00:12:45,761
yet drench the snows of Mars

243
00:12:46,481 --> 00:12:47,561
with innocent blood.

244
00:12:48,841 --> 00:12:51,321
They could slaughter
whole civilizations,

245
00:12:51,401 --> 00:12:53,681
yet weep with the crushing of a flower.

246
00:12:56,361 --> 00:12:57,561
Like the Vikings.

247
00:12:59,681 --> 00:13:00,681
Yes.

248
00:13:02,081 --> 00:13:03,521
-Yes, very much.
-Yeah.

249
00:13:03,921 --> 00:13:07,841
Kirk Douglas and Tony Curtis.
Ah, the theme tune is amazing.

250
00:13:08,361 --> 00:13:09,761
There's this brilliant bit

251
00:13:09,841 --> 00:13:11,801
where, where his eye gets gouged out...

252
00:13:23,201 --> 00:13:24,641
Why have you really come back?

253
00:13:25,081 --> 00:13:26,081
(SIGHS)

254
00:13:27,561 --> 00:13:28,681
I'm old.

255
00:13:29,081 --> 00:13:30,081
And tired.

256
00:13:31,001 --> 00:13:32,001
And spent.

257
00:13:40,201 --> 00:13:41,241
(WHIRRING)

258
00:13:48,361 --> 00:13:50,321
Now then, Vincey. Look lively, lad.

259
00:13:50,681 --> 00:13:51,681
JACKDAW: What's the point though?

260
00:13:51,761 --> 00:13:54,241
-Jackdaw...
-Months we've been digging here.

261
00:13:54,401 --> 00:13:56,041
And what have we got to show for it?

262
00:13:56,441 --> 00:13:58,281
Sweet Fanny Adams, that's what!

263
00:13:58,401 --> 00:13:59,481
ALL: Yeah.

264
00:14:00,001 --> 00:14:02,801
What old Friday promised,
it's a load of gammon.

265
00:14:02,921 --> 00:14:03,921
(ROCKS CLATTERING)

266
00:14:06,561 --> 00:14:07,721
-Jackdaw.
-Wha...

267
00:14:21,401 --> 00:14:22,641
(WIND HOWLING)

268
00:14:36,361 --> 00:14:37,601
You must come at once, sir.

269
00:14:38,241 --> 00:14:39,321
The Gargantua...

270
00:14:39,721 --> 00:14:42,601
She's... She's uncovered something.

271
00:14:46,401 --> 00:14:47,761
Good Lord.

272
00:14:50,241 --> 00:14:52,921
Looks like old Friday
came good after all, eh?

273
00:14:54,561 --> 00:14:56,041
BILL: Oh, it's beautiful.

274
00:14:57,361 --> 00:14:58,521
What is it? A tomb?

275
00:15:00,561 --> 00:15:02,041
DOCTOR: Not just any tomb.

276
00:15:05,121 --> 00:15:06,961
This is the tomb of an Ice queen.

277
00:15:09,521 --> 00:15:11,401
I've a bad feeling about this.

278
00:15:14,961 --> 00:15:17,761
These sarcophagi were sometimes part

279
00:15:18,081 --> 00:15:20,081
of a complex hibernation system.

280
00:15:21,001 --> 00:15:22,881
Sergeant Major, get these civilians
out of here.

281
00:15:23,001 --> 00:15:25,521
No, Colonel, Colonel!
You have to let me examine this.

282
00:15:25,641 --> 00:15:27,921
Well, now, I think not, Doctor.

283
00:15:28,401 --> 00:15:29,761
This is a military matter.

284
00:15:30,001 --> 00:15:32,361
This may not just be a grave
you have uncovered.

285
00:15:32,961 --> 00:15:35,041
This could be the entrance
to an Ice Warrior hive.

286
00:15:36,201 --> 00:15:37,401
(SCOFFS) What?

287
00:15:37,601 --> 00:15:39,041
Sergeant Major Peach,
I gave you an order.

288
00:15:39,121 --> 00:15:40,401
I'm in charge here, Catchlove.

289
00:15:40,801 --> 00:15:41,801
Yes, sir.

290
00:15:42,441 --> 00:15:44,801
-Of course, sir.
-Post a guard.

291
00:15:44,881 --> 00:15:46,921
No one's to come near this thing
until the morning. Is that clear?

292
00:15:47,001 --> 00:15:48,081
Yes, sir.

293
00:15:51,361 --> 00:15:53,361
DOCTOR: The last thing
I'm going to do is take sides.

294
00:15:54,201 --> 00:15:55,441
But isn't that obvious?

295
00:15:56,281 --> 00:15:57,961
Friday's been using you all along.

296
00:15:59,041 --> 00:16:01,721
His aim was to get back to Mars
and find his queen.

297
00:16:01,801 --> 00:16:02,801
CATCHLOVE: Nonsense.

298
00:16:02,921 --> 00:16:04,801
He was leading us to the riches
he promised us.

299
00:16:05,041 --> 00:16:07,361
The simple fact
is you don't belong here.

300
00:16:07,441 --> 00:16:09,361
The sooner you get off this planet,
the better.

301
00:16:09,481 --> 00:16:10,481
CATCHLOVE: Don't belong?

302
00:16:12,001 --> 00:16:13,041
We're British.

303
00:16:14,801 --> 00:16:16,521
Mars is part of the Empire now.

304
00:16:27,161 --> 00:16:28,161
(SIGHS)

305
00:16:30,361 --> 00:16:31,841
What happened to not taking sides?

306
00:16:32,641 --> 00:16:34,161
I'm trying to save their lives.

307
00:16:35,001 --> 00:16:37,961
Let's face it. In this scenario,
the humans are the invaders.

308
00:16:38,041 --> 00:16:41,361
On the other hand, the Ice Warriors
have vastly superior armaments

309
00:16:41,521 --> 00:16:43,241
which will wipe the humans out.

310
00:16:43,801 --> 00:16:44,921
So what am I supposed to do?

311
00:16:47,881 --> 00:16:48,961
Here you go, Sarge.

312
00:16:51,961 --> 00:16:53,601
Much obliged, I'm sure, Jackdaw.

313
00:16:53,801 --> 00:16:54,801
Don't I get none?

314
00:16:55,841 --> 00:16:57,281
R-H-I-P, son.

315
00:16:57,561 --> 00:16:58,561
Eh?

316
00:17:00,121 --> 00:17:02,001
"Rank has its privileges."

317
00:17:04,441 --> 00:17:05,441
Christ alive.

318
00:17:06,761 --> 00:17:08,201
Look at the guild on that thing.

319
00:17:10,481 --> 00:17:12,761
That would set up a fellow
for life, Vincey,

320
00:17:13,041 --> 00:17:14,721
even just a little bit of it...

321
00:17:17,881 --> 00:17:19,561
Now then, you horrible, old man.

322
00:17:20,721 --> 00:17:22,361
Don't go getting no fancy notions.

323
00:17:23,641 --> 00:17:27,521
I'm sure the Colonel will be
distributing this munificence

324
00:17:27,801 --> 00:17:29,361
in a fair and decent fashion.

325
00:17:29,681 --> 00:17:32,081
And we can all look forward to...

326
00:17:33,201 --> 00:17:34,201
To...

327
00:17:35,641 --> 00:17:38,241
A rosy future.

328
00:17:39,201 --> 00:17:40,241
Sarge?

329
00:17:41,921 --> 00:17:43,401
Jackdaw, what have you done?

330
00:17:43,801 --> 00:17:45,281
Acquired that from the infirmary.

331
00:17:45,961 --> 00:17:48,201
He'd be as right as ninepence come dawn.

332
00:17:48,281 --> 00:17:50,721
-But by then, I'll be gone.
-Gone?

333
00:17:50,881 --> 00:17:54,561
Gone where? In case you've forgotten,
we're marooned on ruddy Mars.

334
00:17:55,481 --> 00:17:57,361
You don't know what I know, sir.

335
00:17:58,401 --> 00:18:01,641
Captain Catchlove's further on
with his repairs than he's let on.

336
00:18:02,521 --> 00:18:03,881
Oh, yes, my old love.

337
00:18:04,561 --> 00:18:06,001
Jackdaw's going home.

338
00:18:06,281 --> 00:18:08,601
But this time, he'll be minted.

339
00:18:09,121 --> 00:18:10,281
Come on, give us a hand.

340
00:18:10,841 --> 00:18:11,881
(BOTH GRUNTING)

341
00:18:14,241 --> 00:18:15,281
JACKDAW: Right.

342
00:18:17,641 --> 00:18:19,001
-Keep an eye out, will you?
-No.

343
00:18:19,081 --> 00:18:21,121
You ain't getting me involved
in this lie, Jackdaw.

344
00:18:21,481 --> 00:18:23,721
Oh, go on. Be a sport.

345
00:18:24,241 --> 00:18:25,921
You'll get your share of the rhino.

346
00:18:26,401 --> 00:18:27,481
I promise.

347
00:18:57,561 --> 00:19:00,441
# It's the same the whole world over

348
00:19:03,921 --> 00:19:04,921
(GRUNTS)

349
00:19:06,401 --> 00:19:10,161
# It's the poor what gets the blame

350
00:19:10,441 --> 00:19:11,441
(GRUNTS)

351
00:19:15,841 --> 00:19:19,601
# It's the rich what gets the pleasure

352
00:19:19,921 --> 00:19:20,921
(GROANS)

353
00:19:24,161 --> 00:19:27,081
Z Ain't it all a bleed in" shame? #

354
00:19:27,361 --> 00:19:28,561
(LAUGHING)

355
00:19:57,601 --> 00:19:59,321
(WHISPERING) Someone's coming, Jackdaw.

356
00:19:59,881 --> 00:20:01,481
We'll ruddy swing for this.

357
00:20:05,401 --> 00:20:06,401
Jackdaw?

358
00:20:07,961 --> 00:20:10,001
Come on, mate. Don't muck about.

359
00:20:12,721 --> 00:20:13,721
Jackdaw?

360
00:20:14,801 --> 00:20:19,761
IRAXXA: What manner
of fleshy worm are you?

361
00:20:23,241 --> 00:20:24,801
(FOOTSTEPS THUDDING)

362
00:20:38,401 --> 00:20:39,481
Speak.

363
00:20:43,401 --> 00:20:44,761
SOLDIER: What the hell?

364
00:20:47,441 --> 00:20:48,681
That was

365
00:20:49,361 --> 00:20:50,481
unwise.

366
00:20:51,561 --> 00:20:52,561
(PULSATING)

367
00:20:52,921 --> 00:20:54,001
(SCREAMS)

368
00:20:57,721 --> 00:20:58,801
(HISSES)

369
00:21:00,681 --> 00:21:01,881
(PULSATING)

370
00:21:02,481 --> 00:21:04,041
FRIDAY: Your Majesty.

371
00:21:07,041 --> 00:21:08,081
(BREATH TREMBLING)

372
00:21:09,801 --> 00:21:12,081
By the moons, I honour thee.

373
00:21:12,441 --> 00:21:15,281
Iraxxa, My Empress, My Queen.

374
00:21:15,561 --> 00:21:16,561
My sentinel.

375
00:21:16,881 --> 00:21:19,361
You have fulfilled your pledge.

376
00:21:19,921 --> 00:21:22,921
I am resurrected.

377
00:21:23,201 --> 00:21:24,721
Forgive me, Majesty,

378
00:21:24,801 --> 00:21:28,401
but we have slept
longer than anticipated.

379
00:21:28,801 --> 00:21:31,441
By my calculations, Majesty,

380
00:21:31,521 --> 00:21:35,041
we have slept for 5,000 years.

381
00:21:35,481 --> 00:21:38,681
Five thousand years!

382
00:21:39,281 --> 00:21:41,201
-(ALARM BELL RINGING)
-SOLDIER: Guards, guards, hurry!

383
00:21:41,441 --> 00:21:44,081
SOLDIER: Move, move!
Come on, you lot!

384
00:21:48,481 --> 00:21:49,561
COLONEL: What the devil?

385
00:21:49,681 --> 00:21:50,921
What the hell is going on here, Friday?

386
00:21:51,001 --> 00:21:53,201
Colonel, let me speak to them.
I can do this. I can sort this out.

387
00:21:53,281 --> 00:21:54,401
Who the devil is this?

388
00:21:54,881 --> 00:21:58,001
She is Iraxxa, Empress of Mars.

389
00:21:58,601 --> 00:21:59,961
The deuce she is.

390
00:22:00,761 --> 00:22:02,201
You think you can just
go about slaughtering

391
00:22:02,281 --> 00:22:04,241
my men willy-nilly, do you, madam?

392
00:22:04,321 --> 00:22:05,321
Your men?

393
00:22:05,761 --> 00:22:08,321
What does the pink thing say?

394
00:22:08,441 --> 00:22:09,441
Pink thing!

395
00:22:09,761 --> 00:22:10,761
Sergeant Major!

396
00:22:11,161 --> 00:22:12,681
-Call to arms!
-No, no, no, wait.

397
00:22:12,761 --> 00:22:13,961
Wait, Catchlove, wait.

398
00:22:14,041 --> 00:22:15,681
Your Honour must be satisfied.
An eye for an eye.

399
00:22:15,761 --> 00:22:17,401
I am in command here.

400
00:22:20,201 --> 00:22:21,241
All right.

401
00:22:31,601 --> 00:22:33,361
By the moons, I honour thee.

402
00:22:34,801 --> 00:22:36,081
I am the Doctor.

403
00:22:37,001 --> 00:22:38,561
And I beg leave to intercede.

404
00:22:38,961 --> 00:22:41,281
You know my race.

405
00:22:41,521 --> 00:22:42,521
I do.

406
00:22:43,961 --> 00:22:46,881
And I ask mercy for these primitives...

407
00:22:46,961 --> 00:22:48,441
-Primitives!
-Shh!

408
00:22:53,081 --> 00:22:54,081
DOCTOR: Majesty,

409
00:22:55,801 --> 00:22:56,881
the world you knew is dead.

410
00:22:56,961 --> 00:22:57,961
(HISSES)

411
00:22:58,201 --> 00:23:00,001
The atmosphere has all but evaporated.

412
00:23:00,841 --> 00:23:02,361
(WHISPERS) The surface is lifeless.

413
00:23:03,961 --> 00:23:05,361
If there are others

414
00:23:05,481 --> 00:23:06,481
who sleep here,

415
00:23:07,001 --> 00:23:09,401
they cannot survive on Mars
without help.

416
00:23:10,481 --> 00:23:13,201
You must cooperate
if you want to survive.

417
00:23:13,321 --> 00:23:15,601
He speaks the truth, Majesty.

418
00:23:16,041 --> 00:23:18,921
The war, all that we've fought for

419
00:23:19,001 --> 00:23:21,241
is less than the dust now.

420
00:23:24,161 --> 00:23:25,321
And you?

421
00:23:26,521 --> 00:23:27,521
Female.

422
00:23:29,521 --> 00:23:31,201
What do you say?

423
00:23:31,521 --> 00:23:32,521
Me?

424
00:23:32,681 --> 00:23:34,401
We are both surrounded

425
00:23:34,481 --> 00:23:37,161
by noisy males.

426
00:23:38,841 --> 00:23:41,761
I would value your opinion.

427
00:23:42,281 --> 00:23:44,561
Yeah, yeah. Yeah, er...

428
00:23:51,001 --> 00:23:52,321
They're not lying to you.

429
00:23:53,921 --> 00:23:56,361
There's no need
for anyone else to die today.

430
00:23:57,561 --> 00:23:59,041
The humans saved his life.

431
00:23:59,361 --> 00:24:00,641
IRAXXA: Is this true?

432
00:24:00,921 --> 00:24:03,401
His cryogenic cell was damaged.
They saved him.

433
00:24:03,681 --> 00:24:07,161
And made him their pet!

434
00:24:07,241 --> 00:24:09,881
FRIDAY: It was necessary
to dissemble, Majesty.

435
00:24:10,001 --> 00:24:12,361
I thought only of your resurrection.

436
00:24:12,561 --> 00:24:14,881
It was a tactical decision.

437
00:24:15,081 --> 00:24:17,761
An Ice Warrior's duty is to command.

438
00:24:18,081 --> 00:24:19,081
CATCHLOVE: Present!

439
00:24:20,921 --> 00:24:22,641
Iraxxa, listen to me.

440
00:24:23,481 --> 00:24:25,601
The Mars you ruled is gone.

441
00:24:25,681 --> 00:24:27,321
But don't let it end this way!

442
00:24:28,241 --> 00:24:29,561
Fight this.

443
00:24:30,641 --> 00:24:31,641
For the future.

444
00:24:32,081 --> 00:24:33,281
Not a dead past.

445
00:24:38,441 --> 00:24:39,481
(BREATHING RAPIDLY)

446
00:24:40,241 --> 00:24:41,881
-You bloody fool!
-SOLDIER: Sorry, sir.

447
00:24:41,961 --> 00:24:44,121
Down, put your gun down. Halt.

448
00:24:45,081 --> 00:24:46,161
Majesty.

449
00:24:46,841 --> 00:24:47,881
Are you all right?

450
00:24:49,241 --> 00:24:52,281
You ask for mercy for these creatures.

451
00:24:52,841 --> 00:24:53,841
Indeed.

452
00:24:55,161 --> 00:24:56,401
Then I grant it.

453
00:24:56,961 --> 00:24:57,961
Thank you.

454
00:25:03,281 --> 00:25:05,161
They will die...

455
00:25:06,201 --> 00:25:07,441
(WHISPERS) Quickly.

456
00:25:07,721 --> 00:25:08,761
(HISSES)

457
00:25:08,841 --> 00:25:11,441
No! Colonel! Get your men out of here!

458
00:25:11,561 --> 00:25:12,681
Colonel!

459
00:25:15,681 --> 00:25:16,761
Colonel!

460
00:25:16,841 --> 00:25:18,441
Retreat, retreat!

461
00:25:19,321 --> 00:25:20,601
(HISSES)

462
00:25:22,241 --> 00:25:24,641
Catchlove, listen to me.
Your only chance is to come to terms.

463
00:25:24,881 --> 00:25:26,081
But we have the Gargantua.

464
00:25:26,441 --> 00:25:28,321
-Is she primed and aimed, Sergeant?
-Yes, sir.

465
00:25:28,401 --> 00:25:30,041
No, no, I forbid you.
That is not the way...

466
00:25:30,121 --> 00:25:31,841
Oh, forbid. You forbid?

467
00:25:32,361 --> 00:25:34,161
Well, this farce
has gone on long enough.

468
00:25:34,281 --> 00:25:35,481
PEACH: Arms at the ready!

469
00:25:37,001 --> 00:25:38,161
Ready...

470
00:25:38,281 --> 00:25:40,641
No, no. Don't shoot him, for God's sake.

471
00:25:40,801 --> 00:25:41,961
Put it down!

472
00:25:42,121 --> 00:25:43,281
DOCTOR: Put your guns down.

473
00:25:44,481 --> 00:25:45,761
CATCHLOVE: What the devil!

474
00:25:50,881 --> 00:25:51,881
(ALL CHEERING)

475
00:25:52,721 --> 00:25:53,721
That'll hold him.

476
00:25:54,921 --> 00:25:57,001
(BOTH BREATHING HEAVILY)

477
00:26:12,761 --> 00:26:14,801
CATCHLOVE: We're about to go to war,
so it's time you knew

478
00:26:14,881 --> 00:26:15,881
the truth.

479
00:26:16,201 --> 00:26:17,241
Listen to me, men.

480
00:26:18,681 --> 00:26:21,481
The Colonel is not what he appears.

481
00:26:22,521 --> 00:26:24,681
The hero of Isandlwana!

482
00:26:25,521 --> 00:26:27,081
-Show them your famous wounds.
-No, no, no.

483
00:26:27,361 --> 00:26:29,441
-No, please. No, no, no, please.
-Show them!

484
00:26:31,081 --> 00:26:32,081
The mark of a rope.

485
00:26:32,801 --> 00:26:34,841
While you were fighting
for Queen and country,

486
00:26:34,921 --> 00:26:35,921
the Colonel here

487
00:26:36,041 --> 00:26:38,281
was dancing the Newgate Polka.

488
00:26:38,441 --> 00:26:39,521
This...

489
00:26:40,241 --> 00:26:45,401
This is the mark of the rope
that failed to hang him for desertion.

490
00:26:46,481 --> 00:26:49,041
They tried to hang him
but they bungled it.

491
00:26:49,241 --> 00:26:50,881
He's a paper tiger.

492
00:26:51,041 --> 00:26:52,281
Not fit to command.

493
00:26:52,481 --> 00:26:55,201
Look, it doesn't matter who's in charge
of your stupid expedition.

494
00:26:55,801 --> 00:26:57,721
You don't stand a chance
against the Ice Warriors.

495
00:26:57,801 --> 00:26:58,961
What? All two of them?

496
00:26:59,201 --> 00:27:00,761
There will be more, you idiot.

497
00:27:00,921 --> 00:27:02,081
The hive is active.

498
00:27:02,841 --> 00:27:05,961
Don't you see? They'll do anything
to defend their home planet.

499
00:27:07,081 --> 00:27:09,641
Well, I dare say the British army

500
00:27:09,721 --> 00:27:12,681
is more than a match
for a bunch of upright crocodiles.

501
00:27:13,281 --> 00:27:14,401
-Sergeant Major!
-Sir.

502
00:27:14,481 --> 00:27:16,081
I'm assuming command.

503
00:27:16,281 --> 00:27:17,841
Take the Colonel
and put him in the brig.

504
00:27:18,921 --> 00:27:20,881
Sergeant Major Peach,
I gave you an order.

505
00:27:21,441 --> 00:27:22,601
Very good, sir.

506
00:27:23,441 --> 00:27:24,441
Private!

507
00:27:39,841 --> 00:27:42,681
If you would be so good
as to come this way, sir.

508
00:27:42,801 --> 00:27:44,521
Oh, and for the last time,

509
00:27:44,881 --> 00:27:46,961
get these wretched people
out of my sight.

510
00:27:47,161 --> 00:27:48,321
-Put them in the brig too.
-Go on.

511
00:27:48,841 --> 00:27:51,041
There's no room for civilians here.

512
00:27:54,361 --> 00:27:56,721
-This isn't over, Catchlove.
-CATCHGLOVE: No.

513
00:27:57,521 --> 00:27:58,521
It ain't.

514
00:27:59,161 --> 00:28:01,241
Not now Neville Catchlove's in charge.

515
00:28:08,401 --> 00:28:09,841
DOCTOR: You'll regret this.

516
00:28:11,201 --> 00:28:13,281
In a couple of hours,
you'll be begging for help.

517
00:28:15,521 --> 00:28:19,721
It will take time
to revive all of my warriors.

518
00:28:20,041 --> 00:28:22,561
But perhaps enough are awoken

519
00:28:22,641 --> 00:28:26,281
to go on the offensive.

520
00:28:29,881 --> 00:28:32,241
CATCHLOVE: If either
of those creatures get out of there,

521
00:28:33,361 --> 00:28:35,361
-we'll be ready for them.
-Yes, sir.

522
00:28:43,081 --> 00:28:45,401
-Carry on, Sergeant Major.
-We won't let you down, sir.

523
00:28:45,481 --> 00:28:46,481
(SONIC SCREWDRIVER WHIRRING)

524
00:28:47,561 --> 00:28:50,241
There's no setting for wood.
Why is there still no setting for wood?

525
00:28:50,321 --> 00:28:51,681
But you got a plan?

526
00:28:52,121 --> 00:28:55,401
Yes, of course, I've got a plan.
I'm all plans. I'm made of plans.

527
00:28:55,521 --> 00:28:57,481
Who the deuce are you two, really?

528
00:28:57,921 --> 00:29:00,881
You speak of us as though
we're a different species.

529
00:29:01,241 --> 00:29:04,241
You seem to know all about these, uh,
these Ice Warrior.

530
00:29:04,321 --> 00:29:06,241
You seem to know
a lot about most things.

531
00:29:06,601 --> 00:29:07,601
BILL: Well...

532
00:29:07,881 --> 00:29:09,761
-We're sort of police.
-Speak for yourself.

533
00:29:10,401 --> 00:29:11,761
(LAUGHS)

534
00:29:13,401 --> 00:29:15,761
What? You can deal with
big, green Martians

535
00:29:15,841 --> 00:29:18,561
and rocket ships, but you can't
deal with us being the police.

536
00:29:18,761 --> 00:29:21,401
No. (STAMMERS) No, it's just such

537
00:29:21,481 --> 00:29:24,241
a fanciful notion.
A woman in the police force.

538
00:29:24,561 --> 00:29:26,241
-(LAUGHS)
-Listen.

539
00:29:26,401 --> 00:29:27,401
Yeah.

540
00:29:28,201 --> 00:29:31,001
I'm going to make allowances
for your Victorian attitudes

541
00:29:31,081 --> 00:29:32,321
because...

542
00:29:32,801 --> 00:29:35,761
Well, you actually are Victorian.

543
00:29:36,721 --> 00:29:39,081
(STAMMERS) But anyway. Is it true?

544
00:29:39,681 --> 00:29:40,681
You deserted?

545
00:29:43,161 --> 00:29:44,161
BILL: Why?

546
00:29:44,801 --> 00:29:45,801
Oh...

547
00:29:46,961 --> 00:29:47,961
Cowardice.

548
00:29:48,361 --> 00:29:49,361
Simple cowardice.

549
00:29:51,481 --> 00:29:53,481
I thought I had it in me to command,
Miss Potts,

550
00:29:53,561 --> 00:29:55,681
but when push came to shove,
I flunked it.

551
00:29:56,841 --> 00:29:57,841
Deserted my post.

552
00:29:59,721 --> 00:30:02,161
Catchlove's the only one who knew
and he's bled me dry.

553
00:30:05,001 --> 00:30:06,721
(SIGHS) It could have been
a fresh start.

554
00:30:07,321 --> 00:30:08,321
For all of us.

555
00:30:10,121 --> 00:30:11,121
(COLONEL SIGHS)

556
00:30:12,081 --> 00:30:13,081
How's it looking out there?

557
00:30:13,721 --> 00:30:14,721
All quiet.

558
00:30:15,561 --> 00:30:17,361
It's traditional at this point to say...

559
00:30:18,041 --> 00:30:19,041
Too quiet.

560
00:30:26,721 --> 00:30:28,721
(INDISTINCT CHATTERING)

561
00:30:34,521 --> 00:30:36,001
Always liked the Colonel, I did.

562
00:30:36,321 --> 00:30:37,481
Seemed a decent chap.

563
00:30:38,361 --> 00:30:40,521
We must take orders
from the Captain now, son.

564
00:30:41,601 --> 00:30:42,601
Them's the rules.

565
00:30:42,961 --> 00:30:43,961
Sir.

566
00:30:47,681 --> 00:30:49,241
VINCEY: Blimey, Sarge,
this is quite...

567
00:30:49,441 --> 00:30:50,481
(RUMBLING)

568
00:30:50,641 --> 00:30:51,801
...to tell your kids.

569
00:30:51,881 --> 00:30:53,681
I mean Mars!

570
00:30:53,761 --> 00:30:56,961
PEACH: You just face front and mark
your man when you see him, Vincey lad.

571
00:30:57,401 --> 00:30:58,921
I should have known, I should.

572
00:30:59,001 --> 00:31:00,561
VINCEY: Wait till Alice hears all this.

573
00:31:02,081 --> 00:31:03,601
PEACH: Set a date, have you, son?

574
00:31:03,841 --> 00:31:05,041
You and your Alice?

575
00:31:05,121 --> 00:31:08,041
Oh, not yet. When I have enough
put by to make us comfy.

576
00:31:10,361 --> 00:31:12,881
Then we'll get married in that
little church with the twisted spire

577
00:31:12,961 --> 00:31:14,961
back home, down by the river.

578
00:31:17,721 --> 00:31:20,521
Oh, it's so green there, Sarge.

579
00:31:20,641 --> 00:31:21,921
It's beautiful.

580
00:31:22,801 --> 00:31:24,001
I miss the trees.

581
00:31:24,441 --> 00:31:25,601
And the grass.

582
00:31:25,681 --> 00:31:27,801
(SCOFFS) I never want to see red again
in all my puff.

583
00:31:27,881 --> 00:31:29,001
I just wanna see...

584
00:31:29,201 --> 00:31:30,321
(VINCEY GASPS)

585
00:31:34,161 --> 00:31:35,201
(GRUNTS)

586
00:31:37,681 --> 00:31:38,801
(INDISTINCT YELLING)

587
00:31:40,161 --> 00:31:41,401
(LASER PULSATING)

588
00:31:41,601 --> 00:31:42,601
(INDISTINCT YELLING)

589
00:31:43,241 --> 00:31:45,641
How in God's name
did they get behind us?

590
00:31:47,681 --> 00:31:48,761
Turn it!

591
00:31:48,841 --> 00:31:51,361
For God's sake, 90 degrees!

592
00:31:51,961 --> 00:31:53,001
SOLDIER: It won't work, sir!

593
00:31:53,081 --> 00:31:54,161
We need more men!

594
00:31:54,321 --> 00:31:56,641
Catchlove, this is senseless slaughter!

595
00:31:56,721 --> 00:31:57,761
(EXPLOSION)

596
00:31:59,441 --> 00:32:01,441
(SOLDIERS YELLING)

597
00:32:04,241 --> 00:32:05,521
Front, commit!

598
00:32:05,681 --> 00:32:06,721
Fire!

599
00:32:07,481 --> 00:32:09,361
Come on, lads,
there's only three of them!

600
00:32:10,561 --> 00:32:12,921
Sleep no more, my warriors,

601
00:32:13,001 --> 00:32:14,521
sleep no more.

602
00:32:14,801 --> 00:32:17,241
It is time.

603
00:32:23,601 --> 00:32:24,601
(THUDS)

604
00:32:25,841 --> 00:32:26,961
BILL: Doctor, what do we do?

605
00:32:27,281 --> 00:32:28,281
There's no way out!

606
00:32:29,881 --> 00:32:31,441
SOLDIER: Close it! Close the gap!

607
00:32:31,521 --> 00:32:33,561
(ALL YELLING)

608
00:32:33,641 --> 00:32:35,081
(LASER PULSATING)

609
00:32:35,161 --> 00:32:37,681
CATCHLOVE: Retreat! Retreat!
Run for it!

610
00:32:37,761 --> 00:32:39,001
Sir, what do we do?

611
00:32:41,881 --> 00:32:42,881
(SCREAMS)

612
00:32:46,441 --> 00:32:47,441
(GUNSHOTS)

613
00:32:48,961 --> 00:32:51,281
Oh, sod this, for a game of soldiers.

614
00:32:53,161 --> 00:32:54,161
(HISSING)

615
00:32:59,361 --> 00:33:01,241
- (HISSING)
-(GUNSHOTS)

616
00:33:01,721 --> 00:33:02,721
BILL: Friday?

617
00:33:06,921 --> 00:33:09,081
FRIDAY: Doctor, we must work together.

618
00:33:09,321 --> 00:33:13,081
Rise, my Ice Warriors! Rise!

619
00:33:13,161 --> 00:33:14,161
(GUNSHOT)

620
00:33:16,041 --> 00:33:18,321
CATCHLOVE: Regroup!
For the honour of the regiment!

621
00:33:18,401 --> 00:33:19,521
SOLDIER: No way!

622
00:33:19,601 --> 00:33:20,601
(SCREAMS)

623
00:33:22,001 --> 00:33:23,681
Wait, wait, wait, wait,
where are you going?

624
00:33:23,801 --> 00:33:25,641
I'm sorry, Doctor.
Blue funk, can't help it.

625
00:33:26,081 --> 00:33:27,801
I can't do it. I'm sorry.

626
00:33:31,281 --> 00:33:32,441
(FOOTSTEPS THUDDING)

627
00:33:33,361 --> 00:33:34,441
I need a distraction.

628
00:33:35,041 --> 00:33:36,881
-You got one.
-Good luck.

629
00:33:37,761 --> 00:33:38,761
(LASERS FIRING)

630
00:33:40,561 --> 00:33:42,601
-(INDISTINCT YELLING)
-(GUNSHOTS)

631
00:33:45,041 --> 00:33:47,201
Oi! Queenie!

632
00:33:47,761 --> 00:33:48,761
Let's talk.

633
00:33:49,681 --> 00:33:50,681
Woman to woman.

634
00:33:53,881 --> 00:33:55,201
You valued my opinion before.

635
00:33:55,361 --> 00:33:56,401
IRAXXA: Perhaps.

636
00:33:57,721 --> 00:34:00,441
But this is war.

637
00:34:00,921 --> 00:34:01,921
Why?

638
00:34:02,721 --> 00:34:04,081
Why does it have to be war?

639
00:34:04,161 --> 00:34:05,481
FRIDAY: You're Majesty, she's right.

640
00:34:05,801 --> 00:34:09,201
You have forged a new alliance, I see.

641
00:34:11,001 --> 00:34:12,761
Uh, we can stand together.

642
00:34:13,201 --> 00:34:14,441
It's too late.

643
00:34:14,761 --> 00:34:16,561
Mars stands alone.

644
00:34:16,721 --> 00:34:18,081
We are strong.

645
00:34:18,201 --> 00:34:20,761
Soon, all my warriors will wake.

646
00:34:20,841 --> 00:34:24,121
We do not require assistance.

647
00:34:24,321 --> 00:34:25,321
(LASER PULSATING)

648
00:34:27,041 --> 00:34:28,121
DOCTOR: Your Majesty!

649
00:34:28,641 --> 00:34:29,681
Oh, Your Majesty!

650
00:34:30,201 --> 00:34:31,641
I wouldn't do that if I were you.

651
00:34:33,481 --> 00:34:34,841
Stand down or I'll fire.

652
00:34:35,081 --> 00:34:36,881
Fire at what?

653
00:34:37,161 --> 00:34:39,841
Well, geography
was never my strong suit,

654
00:34:40,121 --> 00:34:42,761
but aren't we underneath
Mars' north pole?

655
00:34:43,441 --> 00:34:47,761
Over our heads,
millions of tons of snow and ice.

656
00:34:48,201 --> 00:34:50,561
One good blast from the Gargantua here,

657
00:34:51,201 --> 00:34:53,241
your army will be on ice forever.

658
00:34:53,321 --> 00:34:55,561
Trapped in an eternal winter.

659
00:34:56,041 --> 00:34:57,081
Like...

660
00:34:58,601 --> 00:34:59,641
Like Frozen.

661
00:35:01,041 --> 00:35:02,041
It's a movie.

662
00:35:03,801 --> 00:35:07,521
You would destroy yourself
at the same time.

663
00:35:07,721 --> 00:35:09,601
Well, that's a price
worth paying, isn't it?

664
00:35:10,081 --> 00:35:12,401
It's a simple choice, Iraxxa,
the oldest in the book.

665
00:35:13,041 --> 00:35:14,521
We must live together...

666
00:35:15,321 --> 00:35:16,641
Or die together.

667
00:35:20,041 --> 00:35:21,121
(GROWLS)

668
00:35:21,401 --> 00:35:22,401
(LASERS CHARGING)

669
00:35:23,281 --> 00:35:25,001
You dare to touch me!

670
00:35:25,081 --> 00:35:27,161
CATCHLOVE: Yes, I dare.

671
00:35:29,761 --> 00:35:31,121
Don't do this, Captain.
Don't mess this up.

672
00:35:31,401 --> 00:35:32,801
No choice, old boy. (CHUCKLES)

673
00:35:33,481 --> 00:35:35,321
You, you see, I suddenly remembered

674
00:35:35,401 --> 00:35:38,361
I need a bit of a hand getting
that ruddy ship off the ground.

675
00:35:38,961 --> 00:35:42,401
And who better to ask
than the Ice Queen herself?

676
00:35:43,361 --> 00:35:46,001
Call off your dogs, Your Majesty.

677
00:35:46,161 --> 00:35:47,321
Call them off.

678
00:35:52,001 --> 00:35:53,881
That's better.

679
00:35:57,881 --> 00:36:01,921
'Course, er, I will have to dynamite
the lifts to stop you following,

680
00:36:02,001 --> 00:36:03,001
but, erm...

681
00:36:03,561 --> 00:36:04,961
Well, war is hell, what? (CHUCKLES)

682
00:36:05,721 --> 00:36:07,121
You want to escape, I can help.

683
00:36:07,681 --> 00:36:11,201
Just leave Iraxxa with her people.
Don't mess this up.

684
00:36:11,281 --> 00:36:14,041
Oh, thank you, Doctor, but, erm,

685
00:36:15,121 --> 00:36:17,721
I think I prefer my plan.

686
00:36:19,041 --> 00:36:20,161
(DOOR OPENS)

687
00:36:20,361 --> 00:36:21,361
Gentlemen!

688
00:36:21,761 --> 00:36:24,761
It's been a privilege, however brief,
to command you, but...

689
00:36:24,841 --> 00:36:27,041
All good things come to an end.

690
00:36:27,641 --> 00:36:29,161
COLONEL: I think you'll find, Captain...

691
00:36:31,241 --> 00:36:33,481
-That I'm in command, here.
-(GUNSHOT)

692
00:36:42,801 --> 00:36:44,761
You sacrificed one of your own

693
00:36:45,321 --> 00:36:48,121
without tactical advantage.

694
00:36:48,201 --> 00:36:49,401
No, I didn't sacrifice him.

695
00:36:50,161 --> 00:36:51,441
I executed him.

696
00:36:51,761 --> 00:36:55,681
Do you now expect
your life to be spared?

697
00:36:55,761 --> 00:36:56,921
No. No, no, no.

698
00:36:57,441 --> 00:36:59,001
I expect it to be taken.

699
00:36:59,561 --> 00:37:01,281
And I give it willingly.

700
00:37:01,601 --> 00:37:03,241
BILL: No, no, no, wait...

701
00:37:03,361 --> 00:37:04,441
-(SHUSHES)
-Stop this, Doctor. Stop it.

702
00:37:08,201 --> 00:37:09,441
Some time ago,

703
00:37:09,801 --> 00:37:11,481
I was hanged for cowardice.

704
00:37:11,921 --> 00:37:14,081
The execution took longer than expected,

705
00:37:14,601 --> 00:37:17,201
and I fear I have not used my time well.

706
00:37:18,081 --> 00:37:19,961
I should be happy for you

707
00:37:20,241 --> 00:37:23,201
to complete the work
they failed to do so long ago.

708
00:37:23,761 --> 00:37:26,241
It will be a pleasure.

709
00:37:26,361 --> 00:37:28,401
-No, please don't do this.
-Bill, quiet!

710
00:37:29,321 --> 00:37:30,481
He saved your life!

711
00:37:30,841 --> 00:37:33,961
Your Majesty, I have a request,
if that may be permitted.

712
00:37:34,081 --> 00:37:35,201
Speak.

713
00:37:35,921 --> 00:37:37,361
That man was not one of us.

714
00:37:37,961 --> 00:37:40,241
Please do not judge mankind
by his cruelty

715
00:37:40,321 --> 00:37:41,961
or, indeed, by my cowardice.

716
00:37:42,161 --> 00:37:44,281
Spare my friends and my world.

717
00:37:44,521 --> 00:37:48,321
Your request does you credit, soldier.

718
00:37:49,161 --> 00:37:52,001
It will be considered.

719
00:37:52,361 --> 00:37:53,801
(LASER CHARGING)

720
00:37:54,321 --> 00:37:55,521
God save the Queen!

721
00:37:55,801 --> 00:37:57,281
ALL: God save the Queen!

722
00:37:57,561 --> 00:37:59,441
You will die with honour.

723
00:37:59,521 --> 00:38:00,561
With bravery.

724
00:38:01,001 --> 00:38:05,961
And in the service of those
you swore to protect.

725
00:38:06,041 --> 00:38:07,041
Thank you.

726
00:38:07,841 --> 00:38:09,481
You don't know what that means.

727
00:38:10,081 --> 00:38:11,121
Thank you.

728
00:38:12,521 --> 00:38:14,561
But not today.

729
00:38:17,521 --> 00:38:18,761
In battle...

730
00:38:19,041 --> 00:38:20,041
Soldier.

731
00:38:20,881 --> 00:38:25,041
To die in battle
is the way of the Warrior.

732
00:38:25,561 --> 00:38:30,441
Pledge your allegiance to me
and my world,

733
00:38:31,081 --> 00:38:32,681
and I will ensure

734
00:38:33,401 --> 00:38:35,601
you have the opportunity.

735
00:38:36,961 --> 00:38:40,041
My life and my service are yours.

736
00:38:41,881 --> 00:38:42,881
To the end.

737
00:38:43,201 --> 00:38:44,321
To the death,

738
00:38:45,041 --> 00:38:46,281
my friend.

739
00:38:46,961 --> 00:38:48,641
To the death.

740
00:38:53,161 --> 00:38:54,321
You knew that would happen.

741
00:38:55,041 --> 00:38:56,281
Always been my problem.

742
00:38:56,961 --> 00:38:59,161
-COLONEL: What?
-Thinking like a warrior.

743
00:39:07,641 --> 00:39:09,161
(ELECTRICITY WHIRRING)

744
00:39:14,681 --> 00:39:15,881
(BEEPS)

745
00:39:16,121 --> 00:39:17,121
Ugh.

746
00:39:17,921 --> 00:39:19,001
(GRUNTS)

747
00:39:20,721 --> 00:39:21,721
(BEEPING)

748
00:39:22,721 --> 00:39:23,721
There we are.

749
00:39:23,841 --> 00:39:27,121
Er, I've sent out a sort of
round robin e-mail.

750
00:39:28,161 --> 00:39:31,321
All being well,
the first intelligent space-going system

751
00:39:31,761 --> 00:39:33,281
will be in touch fairly soon.

752
00:39:34,201 --> 00:39:35,521
IRAXXA: Thank you, Doctor.

753
00:39:35,841 --> 00:39:41,081
Mars is dead,
but the Ice Warriors will live on.

754
00:39:44,361 --> 00:39:45,721
Will they make it?

755
00:39:46,601 --> 00:39:47,601
Oh, yes.

756
00:39:48,681 --> 00:39:52,721
In fact, this might be the beginning
of the Martian Golden Age.

757
00:39:53,001 --> 00:39:56,161
ALPHA CENTAURI: Are you receiving us?
Mars, are you receiving?

758
00:39:56,361 --> 00:39:58,521
This is Iraxxa,

759
00:39:59,001 --> 00:40:01,401
Queen Empress of Mars.

760
00:40:01,721 --> 00:40:06,041
Ah, excellent! We have received
details of your situation.

761
00:40:06,121 --> 00:40:09,401
We would be happy to send a fleet
to your aid at once.

762
00:40:09,481 --> 00:40:13,961
A physical marker of some sort would
be appreciated to guide our ships.

763
00:40:14,041 --> 00:40:16,201
To whom am I speaking?

764
00:40:16,561 --> 00:40:18,921
This is Alpha Centauri.

765
00:40:19,721 --> 00:40:21,681
Welcome to the universe.

766
00:40:30,201 --> 00:40:31,201
(BILL GRUNTS)

767
00:40:32,121 --> 00:40:33,121
(EXHALES)

768
00:40:34,081 --> 00:40:35,081
Big enough?

769
00:40:35,761 --> 00:40:37,041
For the ship to see?

770
00:40:37,881 --> 00:40:38,881
I think so.

771
00:40:43,761 --> 00:40:44,761
You gonna be okay?

772
00:40:45,001 --> 00:40:46,641
Well that's twice I've been executed.

773
00:40:47,481 --> 00:40:49,761
Whatever happens now,
it's gonna be better than I expected.

774
00:40:51,601 --> 00:40:53,801
Ah, there's nothing for me
back on Earth and...

775
00:40:53,881 --> 00:40:57,441
To help forge a new world, well
that would be my privilege.

776
00:40:58,441 --> 00:41:00,441
(SIGHS) Seems a shame, though.

777
00:41:00,801 --> 00:41:01,801
What does?

778
00:41:03,081 --> 00:41:07,201
Well no one back on Earth
will ever know that we got here.

779
00:41:07,921 --> 00:41:09,161
All will be forgotten.

780
00:41:09,321 --> 00:41:11,041
Oh, not quite forgotten, Colonel.

781
00:41:12,441 --> 00:41:15,961
You've changed the mind-set
of a very stubborn Martian monarch.

782
00:41:18,121 --> 00:41:19,241
And one day...

783
00:41:20,121 --> 00:41:22,321
Even though the ice cap may obscure it,

784
00:41:23,601 --> 00:41:25,561
someone's going to notice that.

785
00:41:42,281 --> 00:41:44,321
(TARDIS WHIRRING)

786
00:41:49,361 --> 00:41:50,361
(THUDS)

787
00:41:52,681 --> 00:41:54,441
So, er...

788
00:41:54,961 --> 00:41:55,961
What did I miss?

789
00:41:56,601 --> 00:41:57,601
Where have you been?

790
00:41:58,081 --> 00:42:01,081
(STAMMERING) Yeah, er,
before you go getting all frowny,

791
00:42:01,321 --> 00:42:03,361
er, well, er...

792
00:42:21,201 --> 00:42:22,201
Are you all right?

793
00:42:25,881 --> 00:42:26,881
This can't happen.

794
00:42:28,481 --> 00:42:31,081
This is not what we agreed to.

795
00:42:32,161 --> 00:42:34,001
I'm gonna have to put you
back in the vault, you know that.

796
00:42:34,481 --> 00:42:35,521
Sure.

797
00:42:35,761 --> 00:42:36,801
That's fine.

798
00:42:37,921 --> 00:42:38,921
What?

799
00:42:39,681 --> 00:42:42,521
But, Doctor, please, tell me, really,

800
00:42:42,881 --> 00:42:44,041
are you all right?

801
00:42:51,401 --> 00:42:53,241
DOCTOR: The Ninth Legion
and the keeper of the gate.

802
00:42:53,401 --> 00:42:55,361
-They disappeared.
-Except they didn't.

803
00:42:55,881 --> 00:42:59,281
Where is my friend
and what destroyed the Roman army?

804
00:42:59,361 --> 00:43:00,361
(ROARS)

805
00:43:00,441 --> 00:43:02,761
NARDOLE: Something here managed
to wipe out 5,000 Romans.

806
00:43:02,841 --> 00:43:04,361
-(SCREAMS)
-CROW: (CAWING) Doc-tor.

807
00:43:04,441 --> 00:43:05,681
(SNARLS)

808
00:43:05,761 --> 00:43:09,281
DOCTOR: Every hour of sunlight
that feeds it makes the world darker,

809
00:43:10,121 --> 00:43:11,481
and the beast stronger.

810
00:43:12,321 --> 00:43:14,321
(THEME MUSIC PLAYING)

